WEBVTT

00:00:00.320 --> 00:00:13.120
<v Teacher>So, we were learning how we can use the present to talk about the past, using <b>haber</b>, which is <i>to </i> <i>have</i>, in sentences like <i>I have gone</i>, <i>I have eaten</i>.

00:00:13.320 --> 00:00:16.840
<v Teacher>What do you think <b>terminar</b> means?

00:00:16.840 --> 00:00:19.240
<v Teacher><b>Terminar</b>:

00:00:19.240 --> 00:00:20.840
<v Student><i>To terminate</i>.

00:00:20.840 --> 00:00:25.640
<v Teacher>And what, what verb would we use more commonly in English?

00:00:26.100 --> 00:00:26.900
<v Student><i>Finish</i>?

00:00:26.900 --> 00:00:27.620
<v Teacher><i>Finish</i>.

00:00:27.620 --> 00:00:29.620
<v Teacher><b>Terminar</b> is <i>to finish</i>.

00:00:29.620 --> 00:00:33.860
<v Teacher>Do you remember how to say <i>I have</i> from <b>haber</b>?

00:00:34.120 --> 00:00:39.160
<v Teacher>We can look at the two vowels we have in <b>haber</b>, and this will set us off.

00:00:39.160 --> 00:00:40.360
<v Student>Ah, yes.

00:00:40.360 --> 00:00:41.079
<v Teacher>Ok.

00:00:41.079 --> 00:00:42.040
<v Teacher>So, <i>I have:</i>

00:00:44.120 --> 00:00:45.720
<v Student>Is it <b>he</b> or <b>ha</b>?

00:00:45.720 --> 00:00:47.000
<v Teacher>It's <b>he</b>. Good. So, <i>we have</i>:

00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:49.000
<v Student><b>Hemos</b>.

00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:51.000
<v Teacher>Good. How do you spell <b>he</b>?

00:00:54.940 --> 00:00:55.739
<v Student><i>H-e</i>.

00:00:55.739 --> 00:00:59.579
<v Teacher><i>H-e</i>. Good. And that <i>h</i> comes from <b>haber</b>, that silent <i>h</i> that you have there. Good.

00:00:59.579 --> 00:01:02.860
<v Teacher>So, how would you say <i>I have finished</i>?

00:01:02.860 --> 00:01:04.540
<v Teacher>Firstly, how do you make <i>finished</i>?

00:01:04.540 --> 00:01:08.060
<v Teacher>How do you get the word <i>finished</i> from <b>terminar</b>?

00:01:08.060 --> 00:01:09.119
<v Student>-<i>ado</i>?

00:01:09.119 --> 00:01:09.600
<v Teacher>Good.

00:01:09.600 --> 00:01:11.360
<v Teacher>So, you have all the information,

00:01:11.360 --> 00:01:13.360
<v Teacher>now you can build the sentence.

00:01:13.360 --> 00:01:14.880
<v Teacher><i>I have finished</i>:

00:01:16.600 --> 00:01:18.200
<v Student><b>He terminado</b>.

00:01:18.200 --> 00:01:18.760
<v Teacher>Good.

00:01:18.920 --> 00:01:20.040
<v Teacher><b>He terminado</b>.

00:01:20.040 --> 00:01:21.560
<v Teacher>And <i>I have finished it</i>?

00:01:21.560 --> 00:01:23.400
<v Teacher><i>I have finished it</i>:

00:01:23.400 --> 00:01:26.940
<v Student><b>He lo terminado</b>.

00:01:26.940 --> 00:01:33.580
<v Teacher>What is the rule about where this <b>lo</b>, <b>la</b>, <b>me</b>, <b>te</b>, can go?

00:01:33.880 --> 00:01:36.520
<v Student>It's in the beginning of the sentence, actually, isn't it?

00:01:36.520 --> 00:01:40.120
<v Teacher>This would be a simplification of the rule that you might find unhelpful.

00:01:40.120 --> 00:01:43.000
<v Student>Well, if it was in the “to” form it would be at the end.

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:45.000
<v Teacher>So, after the “to” form or:

00:01:45.439 --> 00:01:47.520
<v Student>Or before everything, everything else?

00:01:47.840 --> 00:01:49.759
<v Teacher>Before the changed verb.

00:01:49.759 --> 00:01:51.439
<v Teacher>So this is the way you want to think about it.

00:01:51.439 --> 00:01:54.799
<v Teacher>If we simplify the thought to "at the beginning or at the end",

00:01:54.420 --> 00:01:58.180
<v Teacher>when there is other words there, we might be really confused about where we can put it.

00:01:58.180 --> 00:02:04.259
<v Teacher>So, we must think “after the complete verb”, the “to” form, or “before the changed verb”.

00:02:03.860 --> 00:02:09.539
<v Teacher>So if you say <b>he lo terminado</b>, you’ve actually got it after a changed verb,

00:02:09.539 --> 00:02:10.660
<v Teacher>you put it after <b>he</b>.

00:02:10.739 --> 00:02:15.220
<v Teacher>So, this is a very rare situation in Spanish, where we have two changed verbs together:

00:02:16.659 --> 00:02:20.019
<v Teacher>We see, usually after a changed verb we get a complete verb:

00:02:20.019 --> 00:02:21.780
<v Teacher><b>quiero </b> <b>terminar</b>,

00:02:21.780 --> 00:02:23.459
<v Teacher><i>I want to finish</i>;

00:02:23.459 --> 00:02:25.379
<v Teacher><b>puedo terminar</b>,

00:02:25.379 --> 00:02:27.459
<v Teacher><i>I can to finish</i>;

00:02:28.200 --> 00:02:29.959
<v Teacher><b>debo terminar</b>,

00:02:29.959 --> 00:02:33.079
<v Teacher><i>I must/I owe to finish</i>.

00:02:33.079 --> 00:02:35.000
<v Teacher>So, here we have two changed verbs together,

00:02:35.079 --> 00:02:36.599
<v Teacher><b>he terminado</b>,

00:02:36.599 --> 00:02:37.799
<v Teacher>weird situation,

00:02:37.799 --> 00:02:40.439
<v Teacher>which means there is only one place it can go.

00:02:40.240 --> 00:02:41.680
<v Student>Before the <b>he</b>.

00:02:41.680 --> 00:02:42.160
<v Teacher>Yes.

00:02:42.160 --> 00:02:43.840
<v Student>It's <b>lo he terminado</b>.

00:02:43.840 --> 00:02:44.160
<v Teacher>Good.

00:02:44.160 --> 00:02:45.600
<v Teacher><b>Lo he terminado</b>.

00:02:45.600 --> 00:02:47.040
<v Teacher>And <i>I have finished them</i>:

00:02:48.640 --> 00:02:50.320
<v Student><b>Los he terminado</b>.

00:02:50.320 --> 00:02:52.240
<v Teacher><b>Los he terminado</b>.

00:02:52.240 --> 00:02:57.440
<v Teacher>So, with -<i>ar</i> verbs, we take off the -<i>ar</i> and we put -<i>ado</i>.

00:02:57.120 --> 00:03:07.840
<v Teacher>With <i>-er/-ir </i>verbs, we take away the -<i>er</i> or the -<i>ir</i> and we put -<i>ido</i> to get this form of the verb that we need after <b>haber</b>.

00:03:07.640 --> 00:03:09.799
<v Student>Whether it is an -<i>e -</i> there is no -<i>edo</i>?

00:03:09.799 --> 00:03:17.319
<v Teacher>No. Like I said, there is only one difference between -<i>er</i> and -<i>ir</i> verbs, in all of the Spanish language,

00:03:17.319 --> 00:03:22.360
<v Teacher>only one occasion where they are doing things differently and that was in the present for <i>we</i>.

00:03:22.420 --> 00:03:28.980
<v Teacher>So, for example, we have <b>vender</b>, which means <i>to sell</i>, and how do you say <i>we sell</i>?

00:03:29.460 --> 00:03:30.580
<v Student><b>Vendemos</b>.

00:03:30.580 --> 00:03:30.980
<v Teacher>Good.

00:03:30.980 --> 00:03:35.140
<v Teacher>And we had <b>venir</b>, <i>to come</i>, and how do you say <i>we come</i>?

00:03:35.980 --> 00:03:36.940
<v Student><b>Venimos</b>.

00:03:36.940 --> 00:03:37.740
<v Teacher><b>Venimos</b>.

00:03:37.740 --> 00:03:40.300
<v Teacher>So, we had -<i>emos</i> and -<i>imos</i>.

00:03:40.300 --> 00:03:45.180
<v Teacher>This is the only time in the whole Spanish language that these two verbs are doing something differently.

00:03:45.120 --> 00:03:48.640
<v Teacher>To get this form of the verb that we need after <b>haber</b>

00:03:48.640 --> 00:03:50.000
<v Teacher>everything goes to -<i>ido</i>.

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:51.840
<v Teacher>So <b>vender</b> becomes?

00:03:51.840 --> 00:03:53.840
<v Student><b>Vendido</b>.

00:03:53.840 --> 00:03:54.560
<v Teacher><b>Vendido</b>.

00:03:54.560 --> 00:03:56.080
<v Teacher>And <b>venir</b> becomes?

00:03:57.060 --> 00:03:57.940
<v Student><b>Venido</b>.

00:03:57.940 --> 00:03:58.580
<v Teacher><b>Venido</b>.

00:03:58.580 --> 00:04:02.740
<v Teacher>Now we understand where is <b>bienvenido</b> from,

00:04:02.740 --> 00:04:04.020
<v Teacher><i>well-come</i>.

00:04:04.020 --> 00:04:07.620
<v Teacher><b>Perder</b>, which was <i>to lose</i>, becomes?

00:04:08.300 --> 00:04:09.260
<v Student><b>Perdido</b>.

00:04:09.260 --> 00:04:10.220
<v Teacher><b>Perdido</b>.

00:04:10.220 --> 00:04:10.860
<v Teacher>Good.

00:04:10.860 --> 00:04:12.540
<v Teacher>Now we can make some sentences.

00:04:12.540 --> 00:04:15.020
<v Teacher>How do you say <i>I have lost</i>?

00:04:16.160 --> 00:04:17.120
<v Student><b>He perdido</b>.

00:04:18.560 --> 00:04:24.000
<v Teacher>What if you wanted to be emphatic and used the word for <i>I</i> to emphasize?

00:04:24.800 --> 00:04:26.320
<v Student><b>Yo he perdido</b>.

00:04:26.320 --> 00:04:26.720
<v Teacher>Good.

00:04:26.720 --> 00:04:28.560
<v Teacher><b>Yo he perdido</b>.

00:04:28.560 --> 00:04:35.680
<v Teacher>And, we said that there was a connection between <i>I</i> and <i>we</i>, that <i>we</i> is the plural of <i>I</i>, so this can help us remember

00:04:36.020 --> 00:04:40.180
<v Teacher>that there is a little connection between <b>he</b> for <i>I have</i> and <i>we have</i>, which is?

00:04:40.180 --> 00:04:41.180
<v Student><b>Hemos</b>.

00:04:41.180 --> 00:04:45.180
<v Teacher><b>Hemos</b>. They both use /<i>e</i>/: <b>he</b>, <b>hemos</b>. Good. So how do you say <i>we have lost</i>?

00:04:45.180 --> 00:04:48.180
<v Student><b>Hemos perdido</b>.

00:04:48.180 --> 00:04:48.780
<v Teacher><b>Hemos perdido</b>.

00:04:52.900 --> 00:04:58.820
<v Teacher><b>Nosotros</b>. <b>Nosotros</b> is the word for <i>we</i>, for a male or mixed group.

00:04:58.820 --> 00:05:02.260
<v Teacher>If you are just females, what do you think you might say?

00:05:02.480 --> 00:05:03.600
<v Student><b>Nosotras</b>.

00:05:03.600 --> 00:05:04.800
<v Teacher><b>Nosotras</b>.

00:05:04.800 --> 00:05:05.200
<v Teacher>Good.

00:05:05.200 --> 00:05:07.760
<v Teacher>You pronounced an <i>s</i> there, which was very good,

00:05:07.760 --> 00:05:14.880
<v Teacher>most English speakers find themselves accidentally saying /<i>nozotros</i>/, with a <i>z</i>.

00:05:14.600 --> 00:05:17.480
<v Teacher>Not /<i>nozotros/</i>, but <b>nosotros</b>.

00:05:17.480 --> 00:05:20.920
<v Teacher>It is an <i>s</i>. <b>Nosotros</b>. Or <b>nosotras</b>.

00:05:20.920 --> 00:05:23.400
<v Teacher>So how would you say <i>we have lost,</i>

00:05:23.400 --> 00:05:25.160
<v Teacher>emphasizing?

00:05:25.880 --> 00:05:32.680
<v Student><b>Nosotras</b>- sorry, <b>nosotros.</b> Well, it could be. <b>Hemos perdido.</b>

00:05:33.400 --> 00:05:38.760
<v Teacher><b>Nosotros</b> or <b>nosotras</b> (if you are all females) <b>hemos perdido</b>.

00:05:39.560 --> 00:05:46.919
<v Teacher>So, we had <b>he</b> and <b>hemos</b>, and then for the rest of the versions we go to the other vowel which was in this word <b>haber</b>.

00:05:47.820 --> 00:05:50.220
<v Teacher>So, give me the other versions.

00:05:50.220 --> 00:05:54.780
<v Teacher>Firstly <i>he/she/it/you (</i>formal) <i>have/has</i>:

00:05:54.780 --> 00:05:56.860
<v Student><b>Ha</b>.

00:05:56.860 --> 00:05:59.259
<v Teacher>So, lets start with that one,

00:05:59.259 --> 00:06:02.380
<v Teacher>how would you say <i>he has lost</i>?

00:06:02.380 --> 00:06:03.820
<v Student><b>Ha perdido</b>.

00:06:03.820 --> 00:06:09.100
<v Teacher>Good, and if you wanted to clarify or emphasize that it was <i>he</i> and not <i>she</i>, for example?

00:06:10.100 --> 00:06:12.100
<v Student>Il?

00:06:12.100 --> 00:06:14.100
<v Teacher>Close, <b>él</b>.

00:06:14.100 --> 00:06:15.100
<v Student>Sorry, <b>él</b>.

00:06:15.100 --> 00:06:16.100
<v Teacher>Good.

00:06:16.100 --> 00:06:17.940
<v Student><b>Él ha perdido</b>.

00:06:17.940 --> 00:06:19.400
<v Teacher>And <i>she</i>?

00:06:19.400 --> 00:06:20.280
<v Student>La?

00:06:20.280 --> 00:06:23.640
<v Teacher>So, you must differentiate between <i>she</i> and <i>her</i>,

00:06:23.640 --> 00:06:28.360
<v Teacher>don't just let that feminine idea come in your mind and pick one of these.

00:06:28.360 --> 00:06:30.840
<v Teacher>You must take the time to decide which one is it.

00:06:30.840 --> 00:06:33.000
<v Teacher>Is it <i>she</i> or is it <i>her</i>?

00:06:33.160 --> 00:06:33.960
<v Student><b>Ella</b>.

00:06:33.960 --> 00:06:34.360
<v Teacher>Good.

00:06:34.360 --> 00:06:36.520
<v Teacher>So <i>she has lost</i>:

00:06:36.520 --> 00:06:38.600
<v Student><b>Ella ha perdido</b>.

00:06:38.600 --> 00:06:39.480
<v Teacher>Good.

00:06:39.800 --> 00:06:41.560
<v Teacher><i>You have lost</i>, informally:

00:06:43.360 --> 00:06:44.720
<v Student><b>Has perdido</b>.

00:06:44.720 --> 00:06:45.600
<v Teacher>Good.

00:06:45.600 --> 00:06:54.320
<v Teacher>Now, if you want to emphasize, if you want to say <i>YOU have lost,</i> the word for <i>you</i>, for informal, is <b>tú</b>

00:06:54.320 --> 00:06:55.360
<v Teacher>(<i>t-ú</i>). <b>Tú</b>.

00:06:55.360 --> 00:06:56.480
<v Student><b>Tú has perdido</b>.

00:06:56.480 --> 00:06:58.080
<v Teacher>Good. <b>Tú has perdido</b>.

00:06:58.080 --> 00:07:01.360
<v Teacher>What was <i>I love you</i>?

00:07:01.360 --> 00:07:02.800
<v Student><b>Te quiero</b>.

00:07:02.800 --> 00:07:03.680
<v Teacher><b>Te quiero</b>.

00:07:03.680 --> 00:07:07.280
<v Teacher>So, what is the difference between <b>tú</b> and <b>te</b>?

00:07:07.020 --> 00:07:12.940
<v Teacher>It is the same as the difference between <i>she</i> and <i>her</i>, and <i>he</i> and <i>him</i>,

00:07:12.940 --> 00:07:16.300
<v Teacher>only in English we don't have two separate words

00:07:16.020 --> 00:07:20.100
<v Teacher>for <i>you</i> and <i>you</i> in those two different positions.

00:07:20.100 --> 00:07:23.300
<v Teacher><i>He sees, I see him</i>.

00:07:23.300 --> 00:07:25.140
<v Teacher>So, <i>he sees</i>, we use <i>he</i>.

00:07:25.140 --> 00:07:27.140
<v Teacher>Then <i>I see him</i>, we use <i>him</i>.

00:07:27.140 --> 00:07:29.060
<v Teacher>This is very intuitive to us in English,

00:07:29.060 --> 00:07:30.580
<v Teacher>we don't think about it.

00:07:30.620 --> 00:07:33.500
<v Teacher><i>She sees, I see her</i>.

00:07:33.500 --> 00:07:35.020
<v Teacher>There we have the same change.

00:07:35.020 --> 00:07:36.780
<v Teacher>But <i>you</i> doesn't change,

00:07:36.780 --> 00:07:39.099
<v Teacher><i>you see, I see you</i>.

00:07:39.160 --> 00:07:42.760
<v Teacher>So, that might confuse us in Spanish because in English it doesn't change,

00:07:42.760 --> 00:07:48.280
<v Teacher>but all we need to understand is that <b>tú</b> goes in the group of <b>él</b>, <b>ella</b>,

00:07:48.240 --> 00:07:58.240
<v Teacher><b>yo</b>: <b>tú</b> (<i>you</i>); and <b>te</b> is in the group of those little words, <b>lo</b>, <b>la</b>, <b>me</b>: <b>te</b>. So, lets practise this. What was <i>to see </i>or <i>to view</i>?

00:07:59.140 --> 00:07:59.860
<v Student><b>Ver</b>?

00:07:59.860 --> 00:08:00.500
<v Teacher><b>Ver</b>.

00:08:00.500 --> 00:08:03.140
<v Teacher>And <i>I see</i> is a little bit irregular,

00:08:03.140 --> 00:08:04.980
<v Teacher>do you remember how it was?

00:08:05.540 --> 00:08:06.260
<v Student><b>Veo</b>.

00:08:06.260 --> 00:08:11.700
<v Teacher>So, how would you say <i>I see it,</i><i>I see him</i> or <i>I see you</i> (formal)?

00:08:12.400 --> 00:08:13.360
<v Student><b>Lo veo</b>.

00:08:13.360 --> 00:08:14.320
<v Teacher><b>Lo veo</b>.

00:08:14.320 --> 00:08:15.280
<v Teacher>Good.

00:08:15.280 --> 00:08:24.480
<v Teacher><i>I see her</i> or <i>I see it </i>(feminine thing) or <i>I see you</i> speaking formally to a female?

00:08:25.460 --> 00:08:26.740
<v Student><b>La veo</b>.

00:08:26.740 --> 00:08:27.780
<v Teacher><b>La veo</b>.

00:08:27.780 --> 00:08:30.740
<v Teacher>Or how would you say <i>I see them</i> (females)

00:08:30.740 --> 00:08:33.860
<v Teacher>or <i>I see you</i> (plural, all females)

00:08:33.860 --> 00:08:37.219
<v Teacher>or <i>I see them</i> (feminine objects)?

00:08:38.060 --> 00:08:39.500
<v Student><b>Las veo</b>.

00:08:39.500 --> 00:08:39.819
<v Teacher>Good.

00:08:39.819 --> 00:08:43.579
<v Teacher>And what if they were masculine or mixed objects or people?

00:08:44.060 --> 00:08:45.420
<v Student><b>Los veo</b>.

00:08:45.420 --> 00:08:46.300
<v Teacher>Good.

00:08:46.140 --> 00:08:47.180
<v Teacher>One set of words

00:08:47.180 --> 00:08:48.620
<v Teacher>we have <b>me</b> for <i>me,</i>

00:08:48.620 --> 00:08:50.860
<v Teacher>we have <b>te</b> for <i>you</i> (informal),

00:08:50.860 --> 00:08:55.580
<v Teacher>we have <b>lo</b> for <i>he</i>, for masculine object,

00:08:55.740 --> 00:09:03.660
<v Teacher><i>you</i> (formal) or even for neuter, which kind of just means when something doesn't have gender, maybe you'd say <i>I want to see it</i>

00:09:03.740 --> 00:09:08.940
<v Teacher>and that <i>it</i> refers to a situation or something like this, you will use a

00:09:08.940 --> 00:09:12.540
<v Teacher>and then from this the other ones come, but building from <b>lo</b>,

00:09:12.540 --> 00:09:16.460
<v Teacher>so you change the <i>o</i> to <i>a</i>, to make it feminine, and you add your -<i>s</i>

00:09:16.759 --> 00:09:17.720
<v Teacher>for plural.

00:09:18.199 --> 00:09:22.199
<v Teacher>Which means one sound is left in this little set which is <i>us</i>,

00:09:22.199 --> 00:09:24.279
<v Teacher>do you remember how is <i>us</i>?

00:09:24.600 --> 00:09:25.399
<v Student><b>Nos</b>.

00:09:25.399 --> 00:09:26.120
<v Teacher><b>Nos</b>.

00:09:26.120 --> 00:09:26.600
<v Teacher>Good.

00:09:26.600 --> 00:09:28.519
<v Teacher>So this is one set.

00:09:28.520 --> 00:09:30.440
<v Teacher>Now lets practice the other set.

00:09:30.440 --> 00:09:33.480
<v Teacher>How do you say <i>he sees</i>?

00:09:33.480 --> 00:09:34.760
<v Student>Is it <b>ve</b>?

00:09:34.760 --> 00:09:35.160
<v Teacher>Good.

00:09:35.160 --> 00:09:38.360
<v Teacher>And what if you want to clarify or emphasize?

00:09:40.920 --> 00:09:42.000
<v Student><b>Él ve</b>.

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:44.000
<v Teacher><b>Él ve</b>. Good. <i>She sees</i>:

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:46.000
<v Student><b>Ella ve</b>.

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:49.000
<v Teacher><b>Ella ve</b>. Good. <i>I see</i>:

00:09:50.620 --> 00:09:52.140
<v Student><b>Yo veo</b>.

00:09:52.140 --> 00:09:52.940
<v Teacher>Good.

00:09:52.940 --> 00:09:56.620
<v Teacher>Now we said the word for <i>we</i> is <b>nosotros</b>,

00:09:56.620 --> 00:09:57.580
<v Teacher>not <i>us</i>,

00:09:57.580 --> 00:09:58.940
<v Teacher><i>us</i> is <b>nos</b>.

00:09:58.940 --> 00:10:00.780
<v Teacher><i>We</i> is <b>nosotros</b>.

00:10:00.780 --> 00:10:01.580
<v Teacher>So <i>we see</i>:

00:10:03.680 --> 00:10:04.959
<v Student><b>Nosotros vemos</b>.

00:10:04.959 --> 00:10:06.399
<v Teacher><b>Nosotros vemos</b>.

00:10:06.399 --> 00:10:07.360
<v Teacher>Good.

00:10:07.680 --> 00:10:11.680
<v Teacher>We said that <i>you </i>(informal) was <b>tú</b>.

00:10:12.820 --> 00:10:16.500
<v Teacher>The <i>you</i> in <i>you see</i>, <b>tú ves</b>.

00:10:16.500 --> 00:10:22.820
<v Teacher>Which means that we have also the formal <i>you</i> to learn, which is <b>usted</b>. <b>Usted</b>.

00:10:23.339 --> 00:10:24.220
<v Student><b>Usted</b>.

00:10:24.220 --> 00:10:25.899
<v Teacher><b>Usted</b>. Which is the formal <i>you</i>,

00:10:25.899 --> 00:10:30.699
<v Teacher>it is actually a contraction of <b>vuestra merced</b>, which means <i>your </i> <i>honour</i>.

00:10:30.699 --> 00:10:33.819
<v Teacher>Something like this contracted to <b>usted</b>.

00:10:33.540 --> 00:10:35.620
<v Teacher>So this is the formal <i>you</i>.

00:10:35.620 --> 00:10:39.140
<v Teacher>So how would you say <i>you see </i>talking formally?

00:10:40.339 --> 00:10:41.940
<v Student><b>Usted ve</b>.

00:10:41.940 --> 00:10:42.660
<v Teacher>Good.

00:10:42.660 --> 00:10:46.019
<v Teacher><i>You see it</i> (talking formally):

00:10:46.960 --> 00:10:48.720
<v Student><b>Lo ve usted</b>?

00:10:48.720 --> 00:10:51.040
<v Teacher>Or <b>usted lo ve</b>. It can be either way.

00:10:51.040 --> 00:10:54.880
<v Teacher>The word order in Spanish is much more flexible than in English.

00:10:54.880 --> 00:10:56.240
<v Teacher><b>Lo ve usted</b>.

00:10:56.240 --> 00:10:58.640
<v Teacher><b>Usted lo ve</b>. Either way.

00:10:59.079 --> 00:11:03.959
<v Teacher>How would you say <i>you see them</i> (still talking formally)?

00:11:04.040 --> 00:11:06.199
<v Student><b>Usted ve los</b>.

00:11:06.600 --> 00:11:07.639
<v Student>Sorry! <b>Los ve</b>.

00:11:07.639 --> 00:11:08.040
<v Teacher>Good.

00:11:08.040 --> 00:11:09.480
<v Teacher><b>Usted los ve</b>.

00:11:09.480 --> 00:11:09.639
<v Teacher>Good.

00:11:09.639 --> 00:11:11.240
<v Teacher>So, <b>usted</b> is flexible.

00:11:11.240 --> 00:11:13.079
<v Teacher><b>Los</b> is not flexible.

00:11:13.180 --> 00:11:16.220
<v Teacher><b>Usted los ve</b>. <b>Los ve usted</b>.

00:11:16.220 --> 00:11:22.620
<v Teacher>Now, the word for <i>they</i>, the word for <i>they</i> is <b>ellos</b>

00:11:22.440 --> 00:11:31.160
<v Teacher>(<i>e-l-l-o-s</i>, and this <i>l-l </i>in most Spanish dialects makes a /<i>y</i>/ sound.

00:11:30.640 --> 00:11:39.680
<v Teacher>You might hear /<i>ezhos</i>/ around Río de la Plata in Buenos Aires of Argentina; Montevideo, Uruguay.

00:11:39.680 --> 00:11:45.360
<v Teacher>You might hear like a /<i>j</i>/ kind of sound in Colombia /<i>ejos</i>/.

00:11:44.660 --> 00:11:49.780
<v Teacher>But in the great majority of the Spanish speaking world double <i>l</i> and <i>y</i> make /<i>y</i>/:

00:11:49.940 --> 00:11:51.860
<v Teacher>/<i>eyos</i>/ or /<i>eyas</i>/.

00:11:51.860 --> 00:11:53.780
<v Teacher>I am sure you can work out the difference between the two.

00:11:53.780 --> 00:11:56.260
<v Teacher>What is the difference between <b>ellos</b> and <b>ellas</b>?

00:11:56.579 --> 00:12:01.540
<v Student><b>Ellos</b> is for males, or mixed group, and <b>ellas</b> is for females.

00:12:01.540 --> 00:12:01.860
<v Teacher>Good.

00:12:01.860 --> 00:12:07.060
<v Teacher>So, how would you say <i>they see</i> emphasizing or clarifying that it's <i>they</i>?

00:12:08.600 --> 00:12:10.680
<v Student><b>Ellos</b> is it <b>ven</b>?

00:12:10.680 --> 00:12:11.560
<v Teacher>Yes!

00:12:12.040 --> 00:12:15.000
<v Teacher><b>Ellos ven</b>. <i>They see them</i>:

00:12:19.500 --> 00:12:21.180
<v Student><b>Ellos los ven</b>.

00:12:21.180 --> 00:12:21.500
<v Teacher>Good.

00:12:21.500 --> 00:12:23.980
<v Teacher>Or we could have had any combination of gender:

00:12:23.980 --> 00:12:29.100
<v Teacher><b>ellas los ven, ellas las ven, </b> <b>ellos las ven</b>, etc.

00:12:29.259 --> 00:12:32.380
<v Teacher>How would you say: <i>they see me</i>?

00:12:32.380 --> 00:12:35.259
<v Student><b>Ellos me ven</b>.

00:12:35.259 --> 00:12:35.740
<v Teacher>Good.

00:12:35.740 --> 00:12:37.259
<v Teacher><b>Ellos me ven</b>.

00:12:37.259 --> 00:12:42.779
<v Teacher>So we are understanding that we have two separate groups of very important words.

00:12:42.920 --> 00:12:53.399
<v Teacher>The set of: <b>yo, él, ella, ellos, ellas, nosotros, tú</b>, and <b>usted</b>.

00:12:53.660 --> 00:12:55.579
<v Teacher><b>Yo veo</b>. <b>Tú ves</b>.

00:12:55.579 --> 00:12:59.819
<v Teacher><b>Usted/él/ella ve</b>.

00:12:59.819 --> 00:13:04.220
<v Teacher><b>Ellos</b> or <b>ellas ven</b>. And <b>nosotros vemos</b>.

00:13:03.860 --> 00:13:09.780
<v Teacher>Then we have the other set of words - <b>me, lo, la, los, las, nos, te</b>.
